{"id": 8490, "date": "1972-01-06T11:00:00", "date_gmt": "1972-01-06T19:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=8490"}, "modified": "2026-05-10T09:07:30", "modified_gmt": "2026-05-10T16:07:30", "slug": "roll-of-the-dice-sometimes-at-night", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/06/roll-of-the-dice-sometimes-at-night/", "title": {"rendered": "Sometimes at Night"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>Longtime readers know that while I love Bruce&#8217;s music from pretty much any era, I&#8217;m particularly fond of The Bruce Springsteen Band era of 1971-1972.</p>\n<p>The Bruce Springsteen Band consisted of future E Street Band members (Bruce, Steve, Garry, Vini Lopez, and Dave Sancious) plus horns and backing vocalists. Bluesy and brassy, the band presaged in a way the big band incarnation of the E Street Band still fifty years(!) down the road.</p>\n<p>Several songs from this era have surfaced on bootlegs; check out &#8220;Dance Dance Dance,&#8221; &#8220;It&#8217;s Time to Go Home,&#8221; and &#8220;When You Dance&#8221; for some great examples.</p>\n<p>But many still haven&#8217;t, including &#8220;Sometimes at Night,&#8221; known to have been played by The Bruce Springsteen Band on at least one summer night in 1971, thanks to the surviving setlist below.</p>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"10280\" data-permalink=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/06/roll-of-the-dice-sometimes-at-night/setlist/#main\" data-orig-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/setlist.jpg?fit=407%2C640&amp;ssl=1\" data-orig-size=\"407,640\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"setlist\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-large-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/setlist.jpg?fit=407%2C640&amp;ssl=1\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-10280 size-full\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/setlist.jpg?resize=407%2C640&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"407\" height=\"640\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/setlist.jpg?w=407&amp;ssl=1 407w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/setlist.jpg?resize=191%2C300&amp;ssl=1 191w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 407px) 100vw, 407px\" /></p>\n<p>But no audio of &#8220;Sometimes at Night&#8221; has ever turned up. So imagine the surprise of fans who discovered this handwritten lyrics sheet on display at the Brussels Hard Rock Cafe in 2013:</p>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"10281\" data-permalink=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/01/06/roll-of-the-dice-sometimes-at-night/sometimesatnight_lyrics/#main\" data-orig-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/sometimesatnight_lyrics.jpg?fit=764%2C1024&amp;ssl=1\" data-orig-size=\"764,1024\" data-comments-opened=\"1\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"sometimesatnight_lyrics\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-large-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/sometimesatnight_lyrics.jpg?fit=758%2C1016&amp;ssl=1\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-10281 size-full\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/sometimesatnight_lyrics.jpg?resize=758%2C1016&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"758\" height=\"1016\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/sometimesatnight_lyrics.jpg?w=764&amp;ssl=1 764w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/sometimesatnight_lyrics.jpg?resize=224%2C300&amp;ssl=1 224w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 758px) 100vw, 758px\" /></p>\n<p>It&#8217;s only the first page of the song&#8211;almost certainly just the set-up&#8211;and since the song is known to have been performed live, we can assume that Bruce eventually finished it. But it&#8217;s enough to give us some insight into the song&#8217;s subject:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>Sometimes at night I lie awake for a while</em><br />\n<em>Thinking and dreaming &#8217;bout when I was a small boy child</em><br />\n<em>Running and laughing as hard as I could</em><br />\n<em>Everything easy, everything good</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>I&#8217;m older now that&#8217;s what the judge said</em><br />\n<em>As I walked through the county hall, through a window I fled</em><br />\n<em>The last thing that they did was put a price on my head</em><br />\n<em>Now alone, scared, and running for something I never did</em></p>\n<p>That&#8217;s a terrific opening. Note how Bruce deftly establishes a dreamlike, nostalgic first verse and contrasts it with a suspenseful escape from the law in the second, using a parallel &#8220;running&#8221; device to convey first freedom, then fright. Great songwriting there.</p>\n<p>Fascinatingly, we can also see Bruce&#8217;s first attempt at the second verse, crossed out, but still quite readable:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>I&#8217;m older now, that&#8217;s what the judge said</em><br />\n<em>So now I walk the road with a price on my head</em><br />\n<em>The last thing that they did</em></p>\n<p>It looks like Bruce abandoned that version because he wanted to establish the escape as a contrasting device, but I actually like that version better. One of Bruce&#8217;s songwriting strengths is his ability to provide just enough context and then trust the listener to fill in the missing events. (See &#8220;Highway 29&#8221; for perhaps the best example of this.) Perhaps Bruce hadn&#8217;t honed that skill at the time, or perhaps he wasn&#8217;t quite so confident a songwriter yet. Either way, the &#8220;through a window I fled&#8221; replacement isn&#8217;t nearly as sure-footed as the rest of the song.</p>\n<p>But that&#8217;s a picked nit. The lyrics above are still a great set-up for a song that seems like it would have been a great <em>Nebraska</em> candidate, and I can only hope an audio recording turns up one day so we can hear what it finally became.</p>\n<p><strong>Sometimes at Night</strong><br />\n<strong>Never Recorded</strong><br />\n<strong>Never Released<br />\n</strong><strong>First performed:</strong> July 22, 1971 (South Amboy, NJ)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> July 22, 1971 (South Amboy, NJ)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 May 22, 2019</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>A lost Springsteen lyrics sheet surfaces in Belgium, shedding light onto a performed but never recorded Bruce Springsteen Band song.</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 68889, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_memberships_conta